The article discusses the progress made in building a safer and stronger financial system and protecting consumers from unfair practices. It highlights the creation of the Consumer Financial Protection Bureau (CFPB) as a critical component of the Wall Street Reform bill. The CFPB is taking steps to prevent abuses in payday lending and protect consumers from getting trapped in cycles of debt and fees. The article also mentions other actions taken by the Obama Administration, such as cracking down on conflicts of interest in retirement investment advice and providing mortgage payment relief for active duty servicemembers. However, it criticizes Congressional Republicans for trying to limit the CFPB's ability to do its job and undermining other crucial reforms. The article emphasizes the importance of maintaining the progress made in creating a safer financial system and protecting consumers.